{
    "ocr_text": "LF Jan. 11, 1910 
 
Mr. R. Hungerford, Intl. President 
 Carriage and Wagon Workers' Intl. Union of N. A. 
 434 Sbay St., Toronto, Canada. 
 Dear Sir and Brother: 
 
 Your favor of the 9th instant is received and contents 
 noted. In reply I beg to say that I have an engagement for Sunday 
 evening, and therefore could not see you on that date, as suggested 
 by you. I also have an important engagement for all day Monday, 
 commencing Monday morning at 10 o'clock. However, if you will 
 come up to my house at 9 o'clock Monday morning, and ride down 
 town with me, it will give the opportunity of talking over with 
 me the matters to which you make reference. 
 
 With kind regards, I remain, 
 Fraternally yours, 
 President 
 American Federation of Labor.",
    "summary": "This letter, dated January 11, 1910, is from the President of the American Federation of Labor to Mr. R. Hungerford, President of the Carriage and Wagon Workers' International Union of North America. The writer acknowledges receipt of a letter from Hungerford and mentions an inability to meet on a suggested date due to prior engagements. The writer suggests meeting at 9 o'clock on Monday morning to discuss further matters.",
    "date": "1910-01-11",
    "is_printed": true,
    "is_legible": true
}
